			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">They should have had class definitions for EVERY class BEFORE the game was RELEASED!  They probably did.  And now it has changed.  But IMO, that should be the forefront in every item added to the game, and every spell idea evaluated: <span style="font-weight: bold">How does this enhance the classes it is available to, and how might this diminish the roles of other classes?</span>
<br />

<br />
It should be the forefront of their minds CONSTANTLY, rather than an afterthought that they need to figure out later.  This is the one thing that it SEEMS that EQ2 has done right.  They layed out the archetypes first, and always say "a class can ALWAYS fufill its archetypal role, and no class from another archetype can fill that role."  They designed their game around this.  EQ1 from the first expansion has NOT.  They have even stated they never expected to HAVE expansions, and thus the roles that worked pre-50 no longer did, and it has persisted into the mess we have now with the "holy trinity" (i'm sure that was never predicted), and the "other" classes that can fufill the DPS role to a greater or lesser degree.
<br />

<br />
They are stuck with the fact that many classes do not HAVE a role to play, and are just 2nd-chair to the REAL power in the game.  Perhaps or perhaps not magicians, but we are definitely on the edge of having no role at all, and hence they have to spend MONTHS trying to define us.<br />_________________<br />Eriol Telcontar
<br />
Arch Convoker - Master of the Orb
<br />
