				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Eriol wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">They should have had class definitions for EVERY class BEFORE the game was RELEASED!  They probably did.  And now it has changed.  But IMO, that should be the forefront in every item added to the game, and every spell idea evaluated: <span style="font-weight: bold">How does this enhance the classes it is available to, and how might this diminish the roles of other classes?</span>
<br />

<br />
It should be the forefront of their minds CONSTANTLY, rather than an afterthought that they need to figure out later.  This is the one thing that it SEEMS that EQ2 has done right.  They layed out the archetypes first, and always say "a class can ALWAYS fufill its archetypal role, and no class from another archetype can fill that role."  They designed their game around this.  EQ1 from the first expansion has NOT.  They have even stated they never expected to HAVE expansions, and thus the roles that worked pre-50 no longer did, and it has persisted into the mess we have now with the "holy trinity" (i'm sure that was never predicted), and the "other" classes that can fufill the DPS role to a greater or lesser degree.
<br />

<br />
They are stuck with the fact that many classes do not HAVE a role to play, and are just 2nd-chair to the REAL power in the game.  Perhaps or perhaps not magicians, but we are definitely on the edge of having no role at all, and hence they have to spend MONTHS trying to define us.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
This is what worries me about OoW.  Here they are on the verge of upping the level limit for the first time in how long, and they claim to not have a clue what our class definition is.  I think most mages would understand if Sony told us what their guiding definition is for mages, said that they would use that definition in OoW and then agree to work on existing problems after OoW is released.
<br />

<br />
The answers to date seem to imply they are winging it and that they aren't in agreement among themselves what to do on content.  (Witness GoD and the lvl 70 designed-for problem.)
<br />

<br />
/shrug
<br />

<br />
I give us about 1 in 5 odds that we either hold our own or increase in relative power in OoW.  My money is on the "holy trinity uber alles" that GoD seems to be designed for.  And that means it isn't just mages that are being pushed aside.  What a boring game it would be if we were stripped down to only 3 classes.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
