				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Something funny from my 'Business and Administrative Communication 6th edition' book this semester that I found ironically suits this situation:
<br />

<br />
From Chapter 1
<br />

<br />
Criteria for Effective Messages
<br />

<br />
1.  <span style="font-weight: bold">It's clear.</span>  The meaning the reader gets is the meaning the writer intended.  The reader doesn't have to guess.
<br />

<br />
2.  <span style="font-weight: bold">It's complete.</span>  All of the reader's questions are answered.  The reader has enough information to evaluate the message and act on it.
<br />

<br />
3.  <span style="font-weight: bold">It's correct.</span>  All of the information in the message is accurate.  The message is free from errors in punctuation, spelling, grammar, word order, and sentence structure.
<br />

<br />
4.  <span style="font-weight: bold">It saves the reader's time.</span>  The style, organization, and visual impact of the message help the reader to read, understand, and act on the information as quickly as possible.
<br />

<br />
5.  <span style="font-weight: bold">It builds goodwill.</span>  The message presents a positive image of the writer and his or her organization.  It treats the reader as a person not a number.  It cements a good relationship between the writer and the reader.
<br />

<br />
and...
<br />

<br />
Lost Goodwill
<br />

<br />
1.  The language is stiff and legalistic.  Note the obsolete (and sexist) "Gentlemen:" "Please be advised," "herein," and "expedite"
<br />

<br />
2.  The tone is selfish.  The letter The letter is written from the writer's point of view; there are no benefits for the reader. (The writersays there are, but, without a shred of evidence, the claim isn't convincing.)
<br />

<br />
3.  The main point is buried in the middle of the long first paragraph.  The middle is the least empathic.
<br />

<br />
4.  The request is vague (This deffinition was long- about a paragraph by itself- but self explanatory.  I'll add it if anyone really wants it though.)
<br />

<br />
5.  Words are misused (herein or therein), suggesting either an ignorant writer or one who doesn't care enough about the subject and the reader to use the right word.
<br />

<br />
Kitty O. Locker Ohio State Univ., McGraw-Hill Irwin, 2003
<br />

<br />
I re-read the letter and reply four times now and I really found this interesting.  Just thought there might be a few who would think the same.  I included the full thing because I do not mean to start a flame of any sort by picking out the ones I thought were, well, 'defined'.  I just know a few people here would fine this interesting as well.<br />_________________<br />Missty Cerulean
<br />
65  High Elf Magician
